Try this.

    char[] p = new char[2];

    void someMethod(int number) {
        if (number == 1) {
            p[0] = &#39;a&#39;;
        } else {
            p[1] = &#39;b&#39;;
        }
    }

If you have control over the variables, then you can use an array + mapping logic instead of a multitude of variables and conditions.
Let&#39;s say you have one array and one mapper:

```
char[] p = new char[2]; // or &quot;as many as you need&quot;
static Map&lt;Integer, Character&gt; mapper = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

static {
    mapper.put(1, &#39;a&#39;);
    mapper.put(2, &#39;b&#39;);
    // ... &quot;as many as you need&quot;
}

// number needs to be between 1 and &quot;as many as you need&quot; (inclusive)
void someMethod(int number) {
    p[number - 1] = mapper.get(number);
}
```

But if your mapping is linear 1-&gt;a, 2-&gt;b, 26-&gt;z then you don&#39;t even need a mapper as you can compute the corresponding character on-the-fly.

```
static char[] p = new char[26];

static {
    for(int i = 0; i &lt; 26; i++) {
        p[i] (char) (i + (int) &#39;a&#39;); 
    }
}
```

This being said, you&#39;re probably going down a bad road with what you&#39;re trying to achieve.

1. Your example does not look like Java
2. Your example doesn&#39;t achieve much, logically speaking

I think you should use the following:

    if (number &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; number &lt; 27)
         p = Character.toString(96+number);

97 is the ASCII code for Capital A (A)
You can use a similar method for lower case (a).

